<dl id="n08074k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08074k">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08074k"> 74(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> seldomers &mdash; frequently / drunk than sober</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">we do not hesitate to make new words in <i>er</i> from any verb, e.g. &hellip; a total <i>abstainer</i>, etc. Combinations with an adverb (a <i>diner-out</i> &hellip;) go back to Chaucer &hellip;. Other much-used suffixes for nouns are &hellip; <i>-dom</i> (Christendom, boredom, &lsquo;Swelldom&rsquo;, Thackeray) &hellip;, for adjectives: <i>-ly</i> (lordly, cowardly) &hellip; <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) ?159-60</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02231d" href="c02all.htm#c02231d">VI.C.02:231(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
